agmatism. This fruitful hybridization emphasizes human–technology interrelationships, the role of embodiment and bodily skills, and the inherent multistability of technologies. In a radical argument, Ihde contends that philosophies, in the same way that various technologies contain an ever-shortening obsolescence, ought to have contingent use-lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhenomenology. 0aTechnologyxPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aDewey.  aHusserl.  aembodiment.  ainstruments.  amultistability.  aphenomenology.  apostphenomenology.  apragmatism.  atechnologies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072902340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082326963140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823269631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823269631.jpg  a978-3-11-072902-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK